## Framework 9 — HIPAA

Apply these checks when code references health data, patient records, medical terminology, or integrates with EHR systems.

### ePHI Detection Patterns
- Patient identifiers in logs or API responses: `patient_id`, `mrn`, `ssn`, `dob`, `diagnosis`, `medication`, `icd_code`
- PHI in URL paths: `/patient/123456/records` (IDs in URLs are logged by load balancers)
- Diagnosis or medication data returned without access control verification
- PHI in error messages or debug output

### Technical Safeguards (§164.312)
- PHI transmitted without TLS (HTTP endpoints handling health data)
- PHI not encrypted at rest in database (check column-level encryption or full-disk encryption config)
- Encryption key management absent or keys co-located with encrypted data
- Auto-logoff not implemented for sessions accessing PHI
- Emergency access procedure (break-glass) not audited or logged

### Audit Controls (§164.312(b))
- No audit trail for PHI access (read, write, delete operations not logged with user and timestamp)
- Audit logs not tamper-proof or not stored separately from application logs
- Failed access attempts to PHI not logged
- Log retention not set to minimum 6 years

### Access Controls (§164.312(a)(1))
- PHI endpoints accessible without authentication
- Role-based access to PHI not enforced (any authenticated user can access any patient record)
- No minimum necessary access principle applied (overly broad PHI queries)

### Transmission Security (§164.312(e)(1))
- PHI sent to third-party services without Business Associate Agreement (BAA) verification
- PHI in email bodies or SMS messages without end-to-end encryption
- API responses including PHI without field-level filtering based on user role

